2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those points
- Turn It On Again: The Hits — The description explicitly calls out “lovingly remastered from original analog tapes,” “preserved wide dynamics,” “live‑room ambience,” “minimal compression,” “clear midrange,” “natural instrument separation,” and “layered keyboards/guitars.” Those attributes map closely to my priorities on mastering (transparent, preserving clarity and punch), midrange focus (layered synth/key textures and distinctive lead timbres), and preservation of room and instrumental detail. As a hits compilation it should emphasize the band’s tighter, hook‑driven material (especially their 1980s pop era) rather than long, indulgent instrumental excursions—although the note about “tasteful extended interplay” is the one point that could brush up against my dislike of extended instrumental showcases.
